=begin
  John and Mary want to travel between a few towns A, B, C ... Mary has on a sheet of paper a list of distances between these towns. 
  ls = [50, 55, 57, 58, 60]. 
  John is tired of driving and he says to Mary that he doesn't want to drive more than 
  t = 174 miles and he will visit only 3 towns.
  Which distances, hence which towns, they will choose so that the sum of the distances is the biggest possible to please Mary and John?
  Example:
  With list ls and 3 towns to visit they can make a choice between: 
  [50,55,57],[50,55,58],[50,55,60],[50,57,58],[50,57,60],[50,58,60],[55,57,58],[55,57,60],[55,58,60],[57,58,60].
  The sums of distances are then: 162, 163, 165, 165, 167, 168, 170, 172, 173, 175.
  The biggest possible sum taking a limit of 174 into account is then 173 and the distances of the 3 corresponding towns is 
  [55, 58, 60].
  The function chooseBestSum (or choose_best_sum or ... depending on the language) will take as parameters t (maximum sum of distances, integer >= 0), k (number of towns to visit, k >= 1) and ls (list of distances, all distances are positive or zero integers and this list has at least one element). The function returns the "best" sum ie the biggest possible sum of k distances less than or equal to the given limit t, if that sum exists, or otherwise nil, null, None, Nothing, depending on the language.
  With C++, C, Rust, Swift, Go, Kotlin, Dart return -1.
  
  Examples:
  ts = [50, 55, 56, 57, 58] choose_best_sum(163, 3, ts) -> 163
  # [50, 55, 56] - 161, [50, 56, 57] -> 163, [50, 57, 58] -> 165, [55, 56, 57] -> 168, [55, 57, 58] -> 170 
  xs = [50] choose_best_sum(163, 3, xs) -> nil (or null or ... or -1 (C++, C, Rust, Swift, Go)
  ys = [91, 74, 73, 85, 73, 81, 87] choose_best_sum(230, 3, ys) -> 228
  
  Problem
  Input: two integers and an array
    where, the first integer is the limit distance
          the second integer is the number of towns(elements)
          the third array is the list of distances between towns.
  Return: The largest sum of given number of elements from the list such that the sum is <= the given limit
  
  Examples:

  Expicit requirements
  - the total sum of distance must be <= the max distance provided (first parameter)
  - it must be the sum of second integer number of elements 
  
  Implicit requirements
  - return nil if the list of towns is less than the number of towns you want to visit 

  ## Create all possible subarrays with elements = second parameter

  ## select subarrays whose sums are <= first parameter (max distance)

  ## get the maximum of the sum of those selected arrays 


  ### second way
  ## Initialize a max distance
  ## iterate through all possible subarrays
# - (0..(array.size-(num_elements - 1) do first_indx
    num_elements = (second input - 1)
    (first_indx + 1)...(array.size - (num_elements)) do sec_idx 
        array = [arr[first_idx]] + array[sec_idx, num_elements] 
        max_dist = array.sum if array.sum > max_dist && array.sum <= dist 
        return dist if max_dist == dist 
    


  ## if a subarray has a sum value bigger than the current max distance but less than or equal to the max distance parameter
  ## replace max distance
  ## if max distance is ever == to the parameter, return input parameter 

=end

def choose_best_sum(dist, towns, list)
    return nil if list.size < towns 
    max_distance = 0 
    secondary_towns = towns - 1 

    (0...(list.size-secondary_towns)).each do |idx|
        ((idx + 1)..(list.size - secondary_towns)).each do |ydx|
            possible_dist = ([list[idx]] + list[ydx, secondary_towns]).sum 
            max_distance = possible_dist if possible_dist > max_distance && possible_dist <= dist 
            return dist if max_distance == dist 
        end
    end 
    max_distance
end



p choose_best_sum(174, 3, [50, 55, 57, 58, 60]) == 173 
 p choose_best_sum(163, 3, [50, 55, 56, 57, 58]) == 163 
 p choose_best_sum(163, 3, [50]) == nil
 p choose_best_sum(230, 3, [91, 74, 73, 85, 73, 81, 87]) == 228

